<br>
1) The registration as an islamic immigrant thing:  Yes, Mr Arar was travelling on a Canadian Passport, however, the layover in New York put him under US law, which requires him to register.  As a people have already said, there is no &quot;international&quot; territory in US airports.  The only nondomestic terrritory in any nation is that of foriegn embassies and consulates.  The man was in our territory and had broken our laws, and we have several thousand graves to look at for our reasons to be especially vigilant.<br>
<br>
2) The man had a strong case for holding dual citizenship in both Canada and Syria.  As was stated in the article, the US takes all countries into account in cases of multiple citizenship.  The human rights record of Syria aside, the man was also listed as a wanted fugitive by Syria.  Last time I checked, the US did still have diplomatic relations with Syria, which good faith required us to deliver a wanted fugitive to them.  However, I must admit the fact that Syrian authorities now have no knowledge of his whereabouts other than &quot;we sent him to Jordan&quot; is a bit disturbing.<br>
